                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 41.&#8212;<hi rend="italic"
                                                >Gangrene of toes.</hi>&#8212;<name
                                                type="person" key="600">Private William
                                                Wollcott</name>, <name type="organization" key="645"
                                                >Co. H, 12th N. Y.</name>; age 53; was admitted
                                                <date type="transfer" when="1863-06-22">June 23,
                                                1863</date>, from <name type="hospital" key="173"
                                                >Harewood hospital</name>, Washington, D. C. [The
                                        records show that this man had typhoid fever at <name type="place">White Oak
                                                Church, Va.</name>, in <date type="injury" when="1863-03">March</date>, and that he was received into
                                        Harewood hospital, <date type="admit" when="1863-04-21"
                                                >April 21</date>, whence he was transferred to
                                        <name type="hospital">Satterlee hospital, Philadelphia, Pa.</name>, as stated.] On
                                        admission he was found to have a diarrh&#339;a causing
                                        four or five stools daily, and a gangrene, attributed to
                                        frost-bite while on picket, involving four of the smaller
                                        toes of the right foot and two of those of the left foot; he
                                        had also an ulceration of the left buttock which was
                                        supposed to have resulted from riding in ambulance wagons.
                                        On the 27th the sphacelated parts of the right toes
                                        separated leaving clean ulcers, and on July 4 the first
                                        joints of the second and third toes of the left foot were
                                        removed by operation. Water dressing was applied. On <date type="furlough" when="1863-07-29">the 29th</date>
                                        the patient was furloughed. On <date type="regimenttransfer"
                                                when="1863-09-04">September 4</date> he was
                                        transferred to the <name type="organization" key="644"
                                                >Invalid Corps</name>.&#8212;<hi rend="italic"
                                                >Satterlee Hospital, Philadelphia, Pa.</hi>
                                </p>
                        
